1036
01:33:21,890 --> 01:33:32,733
It's certainly a very good suggestion and it's maybe something that we might come forth to the committee in the future if you so choose to allow us to put the gas lines in.

1037
01:33:33,333 --> 01:33:38,935
It might be a nice project and I would hope that you would show up in support of that if we do.

1038
01:33:41,737 --> 01:33:42,217
Hi again.

1039
01:33:42,778 --> 01:33:57,386
Another thing that I felt to mention is that most of the reason why the people that actually utilize the stove is because we use the oil all year round because this is what we use for hot water to shower.

1040
01:33:57,846 --> 01:34:00,988
So what they in their mind is thinking that

1041
01:34:02,065 --> 01:34:04,966
I'm only getting the fuel system for the winter.

1042
01:34:05,527 --> 01:34:18,632
So I'm going to utilize it and whatever else that I, if I have to force to take money out of my pocket to pay for extra, I'm not gonna heat my home because I have to use that hot water to take a shower during the summer.

1043
01:34:19,193 --> 01:34:30,558
So this is where they're thinking like, okay, I'm saving, but they're not thinking about the safety of that comes along with that, you know, because again, I'm a single mom.

1044
01:34:32,119 --> 01:34:33,481
I know how hard it is for me.

1045
01:34:34,001 --> 01:34:36,424
And it's people that's worse off than me.

1046
01:34:36,984 --> 01:34:40,468
So, and this is also, you know, the concern.

1047
01:34:41,224 --> 01:35:01,194
And at first when we, when Medford Housing had came on board that people were, you know, kind of wasn't, you know, thing, but they were so, I thought they wasn't going to really wanted to go for it, but they were so happy that actually, you know, Medford Housing was going, and myself, was going to take, you know, over and do something like that.

1048
01:35:01,274 --> 01:35:02,235
So it really will be,

1049
01:35:02,975 --> 01:35:24,238
great thing not just for myself but I'm speaking on behalf I represent all the expert housing residents you know that lives there that couldn't be here and and if this is something that you guys really will think about it will be very appreciative not just for us that lives here right now but for the people that's coming my my reason I serve on the board is

1050
01:35:24,640 --> 01:35:26,302
not because I wanted to be known.

1051
01:35:27,142 --> 01:35:45,579
I served on the Medford Housing Board because I was lucky enough to have found Medford Housing when I moved here 17 years ago, that I'm hoping that I'm doing something so when I leave 17 years later, someone else could utilize this and they will benefit from it.

1052
01:35:46,320 --> 01:35:46,620
Thank you.

1053
01:35:49,178 --> 01:35:49,618
Thank you.

1054
01:35:50,438 --> 01:36:08,225
I have one last question which is, how old are these heating systems and is there a concern that the oil burners themselves are potentially dangerous regardless of how the stoves are being used?

1055
01:36:09,285 --> 01:36:11,986
The development was constructed in 1951.

1056
01:36:14,216 --> 01:36:17,919
Gabe, can you answer the remainder of that question?

1057
01:36:17,979 --> 01:36:21,581
So the boilers that are in place now are about nine years old.

1058
01:36:22,422 --> 01:36:28,506
The manufacturer of the boilers makes a conversion kit that you can convert.

1059
01:36:28,687 --> 01:36:30,548
It's called a gas burner.

1060
01:36:30,568 --> 01:36:31,929
It's the front part of the burner.

1061
01:36:31,969 --> 01:36:38,874
You just swap that out and replace the oil burner with the gas burner.

1062
01:36:39,795 --> 01:36:41,076
So it's a quick turnover.

1063
01:36:42,256 --> 01:36:45,857
can hopefully do an apartment in about a day, two days tops.

1064
01:36:46,717 --> 01:36:47,037
Thank you.

1065
01:36:47,918 --> 01:36:54,260
Can I just, before you end, just give you some insight into LaPree Village.

1066
01:36:55,280 --> 01:37:04,963
The Housing Authority on April 3rd underwent an intensive two-day inspection of LaPree Village.

1067
01:37:06,694 --> 01:37:18,400
HUD mandates that housing authorities have the Real Estate Assessment Center, as they call it, which is a separate entity that comes in and evaluates housing authority properties.

1068
01:37:18,920 --> 01:37:24,323
They did this for us in the fall at Bradley Road, Weldon Apartments.

1069
01:37:24,863 --> 01:37:26,664
I think you all might be familiar with that.

1070
01:37:27,285 --> 01:37:30,306
Housing authority, on a scale of 1 to 100, the housing authority received a 95.

1071
01:37:30,346 --> 01:37:31,747
It was 95.3 or .7, something to that effect.

1072
01:37:37,302 --> 01:37:48,566
Points off for things such as one resident didn't have a rubber stopper in the tub, so they took off 0.7 points.

1073
01:37:48,806 --> 01:37:56,708
There was a wall that had a small crack in it on the outside, and they took off three points for that.

1074
01:37:58,569 --> 01:38:04,791
We had the inspection at LaPree, and we have in the vicinity of a 93.

1075
01:38:07,063 --> 01:38:13,188
We went out and inspected each one of those apartments, each one of the 142 apartments.

1076
01:38:14,209 --> 01:38:19,114
And in some cases, we went back and inspected them a second time or a third time.

1077
01:38:19,754 --> 01:38:28,622
And out of the 142 units, we had two residents who were not cooperative.

1078
01:38:29,803 --> 01:38:33,624
Two residents who didn't move their furniture so they weren't blocking a door.

1079
01:38:34,024 --> 01:38:40,485
Two residents who, in the pictures that you see there, the basement, didn't have their belongings in the middle of the basement.

1080
01:38:40,845 --> 01:38:44,106
We had significant cooperation from the residents.

1081
01:38:44,706 --> 01:38:53,988
And to say that a family housing site, the inspection results from HUD, no nonsense inspection, is comparable

1082
01:38:54,857 --> 01:39:01,879
to Weld and Gardens is a compliment to the residents there, is a compliment to our modernization staff, and to our maintenance staff.

1083
01:39:02,299 --> 01:39:11,981
So that when you, if you have an opportunity tomorrow, drive through L'Esprit and take a look at it, and you'll see that the Housing Authority has done a significant amount of work.

1084
01:39:12,381 --> 01:39:16,642
We're moving into Willis to address the difficulties we have at Willis.

1085
01:39:16,942 --> 01:39:22,483
We're addressing all of our projects, excuse me, our developments, and we have projects ongoing

1086
01:39:23,035 --> 01:39:24,236
through modernization.

1087
01:39:24,516 --> 01:39:31,642
We're trying to utilize the money that the federal government gives to us and what little the state gives to us to maximize that.

1088
01:39:32,522 --> 01:39:36,405
We, though, need your assistance to be able to do what our residents deserve.

1089
01:39:36,565 --> 01:39:39,488
And when I say our residents, I'm not talking about the Housing Authority's residents.

1090
01:39:39,568 --> 01:39:40,949
I'm talking about MEDFED residents.

1091
01:39:42,120 --> 01:39:42,460
Thank you.

1092
01:39:44,842 --> 01:40:05,756
All right, so I think that concludes the Housing Authority, and we would like to invite our final applicant up for this evening, which is the Medford Historical Society and Museum, which has two projects, textile collection preservation and museum quality HVAC improvements.

1093
01:40:06,397 --> 01:40:11,080
Would it be all right with you if we did the building improvements first?

1094
01:40:11,593 --> 01:40:13,314
Yes.

1095
01:40:28,121 --> 01:40:34,904
Well, it looks like I've lost most of my audience.

1096
01:40:35,845 --> 01:40:39,447
I'm John Anderson, president of the Bedford Historical Society and Museum.

1097
01:40:40,772 --> 01:40:45,234
And I just want to say briefly about our museum.

1098
01:40:45,854 --> 01:40:47,635
We've been here for over 100 years.

1099
01:40:48,576 --> 01:40:59,961
We have something like 20,000 to 30,000 items in our collection, which we curate in addition to providing public programs.

1100
01:41:00,601 --> 01:41:02,082
We're open on Sundays.

1101
01:41:02,302 --> 01:41:07,765
People come in to do research about primarily genealogy, house history,

1102
01:41:08,631 --> 01:41:12,613
We also have scholars who come from time to time to use our collections.

1103
01:41:14,234 --> 01:41:24,398
I just want to quote briefly from the National Park Service regarding collections.

1104
01:41:25,419 --> 01:41:31,582
They say, many objects will come to your museum collections damaged and deteriorated from use and exposure.

1105
01:41:32,820 --> 01:41:35,521
Because of their history, some objects will need treatment.

1106
01:41:36,001 --> 01:41:40,483
You should develop a treatment plan for immediate problems in your collection.

1107
01:41:41,303 --> 01:41:48,826
Your primary goal, however, is to create a facility that will minimize damage and maintain the collection through preventative measures.

1108
01:41:50,307 --> 01:41:54,330
That's what the focus of this project is.

1109
01:41:54,390 --> 01:42:11,563
What I'm asking your support for, in particular, is a new HVAC system that will enable us to convert from oil to gas and also replace very obsolete air conditioning equipment.

1110
01:42:13,585 --> 01:42:14,025
Let's see.

1111
01:42:17,291 --> 01:42:30,098
Since I last spoke with you, which was when we were asking to be qualified for this grant, I just want to bring you up to date on some of the things we've done.

1112
01:42:30,338 --> 01:42:39,902
Since I submitted the application, what we've done, we've met with multiple HVAC installers.

1113
01:42:41,103 --> 01:42:45,045
We've also completed projects on our own to upgrade the building.

1114
01:42:46,190 --> 01:42:58,524
And volunteers have continued their efforts of cataloging the collection and making improvements throughout the building, such as building shelving, painting, cleaning, and so forth and so on.

1115
01:42:59,545 --> 01:43:01,387
So I'm ready to take your questions.

1116
01:43:06,426 --> 01:43:07,407
Thank you, that was very quick.

1117
01:43:07,828 --> 01:43:11,732
You caught me with my pencil still going.

1118
01:43:12,193 --> 01:43:13,934
I could rattle on if you like.

1119
01:43:14,335 --> 01:43:14,996
That's all right.

1120
01:43:16,778 --> 01:43:18,600
Any questions from the committee members?

1121
01:43:25,341 --> 01:43:27,242
So, I have a question for you.

1122
01:43:28,362 --> 01:43:44,025
You know, given where you are today and what you expect to be able to do with the CPA funds to improve your building, what other capital improvements do you see necessary to bring this building up to the level that you feel it needs to be?

1123
01:43:44,805 --> 01:43:50,927
Well, we had a reserve study done, an engineering study done to look at the long-range requirements of the building.

1124
01:43:54,195 --> 01:44:00,139
Other than maintenance, I would say the biggest thing looming perhaps would be window replacement.

1125
01:44:01,160 --> 01:44:04,542
We had windows replaced maybe 25 years ago.

1126
01:44:04,562 --> 01:44:08,765
They're sort of conventional vinyl windows.

1127
01:44:09,906 --> 01:44:17,412
They were certified as appropriate by the historic commission at the time, but I think

1128
01:44:20,088 --> 01:44:30,853
When we get around to doing it, when we need to do this again, I suspect that the historic district commission will be a little more particular about what we put in.

1129
01:44:31,473 --> 01:44:35,855
I would see that as the biggest looming capital thing, and it's not an immediate need.

1130
01:44:39,233 --> 01:44:44,376
I just have to ask, is there any hope for handicapped accessibility in this building?

1131
01:44:45,117 --> 01:44:45,917
I had Ms.

1132
01:44:45,937 --> 01:44:50,100
McLeod check the building out, in fact, when we first moved in there.

1133
01:44:50,921 --> 01:44:54,664
She told us she had good news and bad news.

1134
01:44:55,564 --> 01:44:58,086
The bad news was we weren't handicapped accessible.

1135
01:44:58,126 --> 01:45:01,629
The good news was there was no practical way to make it accessible.

1136
01:45:02,409 --> 01:45:03,330
The problem is,

1137
01:45:04,696 --> 01:45:08,018
You see the ramp that goes into the front door there?

1138
01:45:09,118 --> 01:45:15,281
If you constructed a ramp the way our property is situated, the ramp would be running downhill.

1139
01:45:16,468 --> 01:45:20,531
And the sidewalk is actually steeper than what a ramp allows.

1140
01:45:20,972 --> 01:45:25,315
So you keep going, you'd have to go across High Street or something.

1141
01:45:28,738 --> 01:45:30,619
You'd have to have a drawbridge on the ramp.

1142
01:45:31,220 --> 01:45:34,642
So she said there was no real practical way to do it.

1143
01:45:34,702 --> 01:45:43,489
The same situation applies to our neighbor, the medical building at 0 Governors Avenue, where handicapped accessibility is even more important.

1144
01:45:47,360 --> 01:45:47,740
Thank you.

1145
01:45:47,980 --> 01:45:49,501
Other questions, comments?

1146
01:45:52,803 --> 01:45:53,484
Come on, Doug.

1147
01:45:55,465 --> 01:45:56,486
You've got to have a question.

1148
01:45:57,166 --> 01:45:57,426
I do.

1149
01:45:57,446 --> 01:46:08,133
First of all, I want to just remind that when the inappropriate windows were put, non-historical windows were put into the Historical Society and Museum building,

1150
01:46:09,270 --> 01:46:10,791
I was in college, I had nothing to do with it.

1151
01:46:13,593 --> 01:46:19,817
That's a small disclaimer, but I do appreciate you undoing a mistake of the past.

1152
01:46:20,037 --> 01:46:25,141
That's really important for building an organization like yourself to maintain a high standard.

1153
01:46:25,181 --> 01:46:25,781
I know because

1154
01:46:27,382 --> 01:46:43,382
You've been communicating with the commission and others about things you're doing, your shopping list of things that you're doing to the building is actually even longer than what you described because you've been reaching out to us for years about that stuff and we appreciate the

1155
01:46:44,163 --> 01:46:47,966
diligence of putting that building and making it good for the next hundred years.

1156
01:46:49,547 --> 01:46:54,330
I guess I do hope at some point there's some creative way to think about ADA.

1157
01:46:55,490 --> 01:46:57,352
Obviously, the street is what the street is.

1158
01:46:57,392 --> 01:46:58,352
You can't do anything about that.

1159
01:46:58,392 --> 01:47:04,716
But within the building, you know, whether we just we had a real challenging time and... Sorry?

1160
01:47:05,157 --> 01:47:09,019
No, I mean, in the building, the steps are too high to go to the next level.

1161
01:47:09,039 --> 01:47:11,201
Again, you'd have to have a ramp down.

1162
01:47:13,418 --> 01:47:19,460
I understand, but we spent 150 grand doing it in the Brooks Estate and that was not easy either.

1163
01:47:20,560 --> 01:47:22,801
Perhaps we had less of a challenge, but it was not easy.

1164
01:47:23,641 --> 01:47:25,061
Well, I'll come back next year.

1165
01:47:25,081 --> 01:47:26,902
Yeah, maybe.

1166
01:47:36,871 --> 01:47:43,336
In terms of schedule, can you talk a little bit about that, about would you do this in the next 12 months?

1167
01:47:43,396 --> 01:47:44,997
I think it's probably buried in here.

1168
01:47:45,858 --> 01:47:52,824
Well, the logical way to do it would be to do it during the summer.

1169
01:47:54,814 --> 01:47:59,177
and it's going to be tight because there are a lot of moving pieces here.

1170
01:48:00,758 --> 01:48:01,859
I've worked with the gas company.

1171
01:48:02,019 --> 01:48:06,301
I've reached out to the gas company and determined that there is a gas line in the street.

1172
01:48:06,582 --> 01:48:10,104
I mean, I've kind of already knew that but you have to get them to say it.

1173
01:48:10,604 --> 01:48:12,265
So we have gas in front of the building.

1174
01:48:12,906 --> 01:48:21,451
The problem is scheduling it so that it can get done and the line can be put in in time but you really have to have a contractor

1175
01:48:22,148 --> 01:48:30,038
and finalize the equipment that you're using before they can really schedule it.

1176
01:48:31,159 --> 01:48:32,721
So we're going to have to get busy soon.

1177
01:48:36,963 --> 01:48:46,290
And you've talked to a number of HVAC because there's some that are more less intrusive visually than others in terms of where the equipment goes and what it looks like within the building.

1178
01:48:46,450 --> 01:48:49,392
Are you satisfied that you have the best solution in front of you?

1179
01:48:49,572 --> 01:48:53,515
We're planning on using the furnace room that we currently have.

1180
01:48:54,396 --> 01:48:56,137
We have this little room down in the basement.

1181
01:48:57,178 --> 01:49:02,542
And in terms of the air conditioning, there's already two compressors in the back.

1182
01:49:03,530 --> 01:49:08,515
which were used for the kind of 25-year-old splits on your split systems.

1183
01:49:09,215 --> 01:49:13,379
So the condenser or whatever you call it, the outdoor unit would be in the back.

1184
01:49:13,579 --> 01:49:13,840
OK.

1185
01:49:15,561 --> 01:49:15,882
Thank you.

1186
01:49:19,245 --> 01:49:20,326
Further questions, comments?

1187
01:49:20,366 --> 01:49:20,446
Yeah?

1188
01:49:23,960 --> 01:49:24,962
Just a couple of questions.

1189
01:49:25,402 --> 01:49:33,876
One, and I don't mean this in any way to be offensive, but given the level of- With all due respect.

1190
01:49:35,522 --> 01:49:51,791
Given the level of investment that the property needs, have you explored at all co-locating with another organization or, for example, you know, the Medford Library is going to be undergoing a major project potentially being incorporated into that?

1191
01:49:51,811 --> 01:49:58,335
I'm just curious about all of that because I know this isn't going to be the last project that you need done.

1192
01:50:02,198 --> 01:50:07,761
